  "chunk_index": 26,
  "summary": "Kanayama reveals that Medvedev, a political prisoner fleeing the Red Terror, lived in the Inagaki family's Kujō residence during the pre-war period. During his stay, Medvedev composed a dark piece titled \"Imakagami,\" which he dedicated to Kanayama's grandfather, Tomomichi Imai. Because Medvedev's name was omitted from a recording made thirty years ago, the work was credited to Imai. Kanayama explains that Medvedev died six months after arriving in Kurosawa City; while his death was officially attributed to drowning in a pond behind the house, the police suspected he was murdered by a communist. Kanayama suggests Medvedev may have been introduced to the Mochizuki family through his grandfather's or great-grandfather's service in Manchuria.\n\nThe conversation shifts to the inheritance of the late Oyama, which Sugiyama estimates to be approximately 500 billion yen, consisting largely of land in the Northern Mountain and Mirai Group stocks. The will cannot be opened until fifty days after Oyama's death, a date falling on the thirteenth of the current month. Sugiyama expresses concern that he may have lost his inheritance rights because his father and uncle were killed before the will could be opened.\n\nAs the group observes Mistuho reading in a pavilion in the courtyard, it is noted that Kaname has been watching over her from a distance for five months. Following her reading, Mistuho heads toward a church located at the western end of the estate. Kanayama explains that his family converted to Orthodox Christianity after returning from China, a rarity in Japan.",
